*Context:*
Adults learning a second language (L2) rarely attain native-like oral proficiency.


Research in second language acquisition (SLA) has proposed various factors which have
the potential to influence the learning trajectory and final outcome.
One such factor is domain-general auditory skills, broadly defined to include acuity,
i.e., ones sensitivity to minute differences in individual acoustic dimensions such
as pitch and duration, and audio-motor integration.
A number of recent studies have suggested that different components of domain-general
auditory skills are be uniquely associated with different aspects of L2 speech
learning (CITE).
However, the exact relevance of these skills also seem to depend on several additional
factors such as the learning environment (naturalistic vs. classroom-based) and
overall L2 proficiency.


